07428nam a22008655i 9781478009009DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20202020ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019016289  a97814780090097 a10.1515/97814780090092doi  a(DE-B1597)552853  a(OCoLC)1153044338  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC00aE185.625b.A74 2020 7aSOC0010002bisacsh04a305.896/07322300aAre You Entertained? :bBlack Popular Culture in the Twenty-First Century /ced. by Simone C. Drake, Dwan K. Henderson. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (335 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tI. PERFORMING BLACKNESS -- t1. “Mutts Like Me”: Mixed-Race Jokes and Post-Racial Rejection in the Obama Era -- t2. Black Radio: Robert Glasper, Esperanza Spalding, and Janelle Monáe -- t3. Camping and Vamping across Borders: Locating Cabaret Singers in the Black Cultural Spectrum -- t4. The Art of Black Popular Culture -- t5. Interview -- tII. POLITICIZING BLACKNESS -- t6. Refashioning Political Cartoons: Comics of Jackie Ormes 1938–1958 -- t7. Queer Kinship and Worldmaking in Black Queer Web Series: Drama Queenz and No Shade -- t8. Styling and Profiling: Ballers, Blackness, and the Sartorial Politics of the nba -- t9. Interview -- tIII. OWNING BLACKNESS -- t10. The Subaltern Is Signifyin(g): Black Twitter as a Site of Resistance -- t11. Authentic Black Cool?: Branding and Trademarks in Contemporary African American Culture -- t12. Black Culture without Black People: Hip-Hop Dance beyond Appropriation Discourse -- t13. At the Corner of Chaos and Divine: Black Ritual Theater, Performance, and Politics -- t14. Interview -- tIV. LOVING BLACKNESS -- t15. The Booty Don’t Lie: Pleasure, Agency, and Resistance in Black Popular Dance -- t16. He Said Nothing: Sonic Space and the Production of Quietude in Barry Jenkins’s Moonlight -- t17. Black Women Readers and the Uses of Urban Fiction -- t18. Interview -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe advent of the internet and the availability of social media and digital downloads have expanded the creation, distribution, and consumption of Black cultural production as never before. At the same time, a new generation of Black public intellectuals who speak to the relationship between race, politics, and popular culture has come into national prominence. The contributors to Are You Entertained? address these trends to consider what culture and blackness mean in the twenty-first century's digital consumer economy. In this collection of essays, interviews, visual art, and an artist statement the contributors examine a range of topics and issues, from music, white consumerism, cartoons, and the rise of Black Twitter to the NBA's dress code, dance, and Moonlight. Analyzing the myriad ways in which people perform, avow, politicize, own, and love blackness, this volume charts the shifting debates in Black popular culture scholarship over the past quarter century while offering new avenues for future scholarship.Contributors. Takiyah Nur Amin, Patricia Hill Collins, Kelly Jo Fulkerson-Dikuua, Simone C. Drake, Dwan K. Henderson, Imani Kai Johnson, Ralina L. Joseph, David J. Leonard, Emily J. Lordi, Nina Angela Mercer, Mark Anthony Neal, H. Ike Okafor-Newsum, Kinohi Nishikawa, Eric Darnell Pritchard, Richard Schur, Tracy Sharpley-Whiting, Vincent Stephens, Lisa B. Thompson, Sheneese Thompson  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAfrican American arts. 0aAfrican Americans in popular culture. 0aPolitics and culturezUnited States. 0aPopular culturezUnited States. 0aRacism in popular culturezUnited States.